{"text": "====== [46.7] The Quantum Hall current\n\nWe would like to calculate the current for an electron that occupies a Landau state l, \u03bd\u27e9:\n\n\u02c6Jx(x, y)\n\n=\n\n1\n\n2(vx\u03b4(\u02c6x \u2212x)\u03b4(\u02c6y \u2212y) + h.c.)\n\n(46.37)\n\n\u02c6Jx(y)\n\n=\n\n1\n\nLx\n\nZ\n\n\u02c6Jx(x, y)dx\n\n=\n\n1\n\nLx\n\n\u02c6vx\u03b4(\u02c6y \u2212y)\n\n\u02c6Ix\n\n=\n\n\u2212\u2202H\n\n\u2202\u03a6\n\n=\n\n1\n\nLx\n\nvx\n\n=\n\nZ\n\n\u02c6Jx(y)dy\n\nRecall that vx = (B/m)(\u02c6y \u2212\u02c6Y ), and that the Landau states are eigenstates of \u02c6Y . Therefore, the current density of\n\nan occupied state is given by:\n\nJ\u03bdl\n\nx (y)\n\n=\n\n\u27e8l\u03bd \u02c6Jx(y) l\u03bd\u27e9\n\n=\n\nB\n\nLxm\n\nD\n\n(\u02c6y \u2212\u02c6Y ) \u03b4(\u02c6y \u2212y)\n\nE\n\n=\n\nB\n\nmLx\n\n(y \u2212Yl) \u03c6\u03bd(y \u2212Yl) 2\n\n(46.38)\n\nIf we are in the region (Yl< y) we observe current that flows to the right (in the direction of the positive x axis), and\n\nthe opposite if we are on the other side. This is consistent with the classical picture of a particle moving clockwise in\n\na circle. If there is no electric field, the wave function is symmetric around Yl, so we get zero net current. If there\n\nis a non-zero electric field, it shifts the wave function and then we get a net current that is not zero. The current is\n\ngiven by:\n\nIl\u03bd\n\nx\n\n=\n\nZ\n\nJl\u03bd\n\nx (y)dy\n\n=\n\n\u2212\u2202El\u03bd\n\n\u2202\u03a6\n\n=\n\n\u2212\n\n1\n\nBLx\n\ndV (y)\n\ndy\n\ny=Yl\n\n(46.39)\n\nFor a Fermi occupation of the Landau level we get:\n\nIx\n\n=\n\nX\n\nl\n\nIl\u03bd\n\nx\n\n=\n\nZ y2\n\ny1\n\ndy\n\n2\u03c0/(BLx)\n\n\u0012\n\n\u2212\n\n1\n\nBLx\n\ndV (y)\n\ndy\n\n\u0013\n\n(46.40)\n\n=\n\n\u22121\n\n2\u03c0 (V (y2) \u2212V (y1))\n\n=\n\n\u2212e\n\n2\u03c0\u0127(\u03bc2 \u2212\u03bc1)\n\nIn the last equation we have restored the standard physical units. We see that if there is a chemical potential difference\n\nwe get a current Ix. Writing \u03bc = eV ,